00:04:11.415 --> 00:04:15.582
Were Williams patients recognized
before genetics started?

00:04:18.207 --> 00:04:20.222
- So that's a very good question.

00:04:20.222 --> 00:04:23.972
Indeed they were
recognized, but not as such.

00:04:24.849 --> 00:04:28.251
I forget the year but decades ago

00:04:28.251 --> 00:04:32.418
Williams and Baron whose
name I always mispronounce,

00:04:33.306 --> 00:04:37.056
characterized a syndrome
that was typified by

00:04:38.329 --> 00:04:41.912
infantile hypercalcemia,
failure to thrive,

00:04:43.152 --> 00:04:44.485
and elfin faces.

00:04:45.438 --> 00:04:48.375
And in fact when I was in medical school,

00:04:48.375 --> 00:04:50.287
and I won't tell you
how long ago that was,

00:04:50.287 --> 00:04:51.610
but a long time ago,

00:04:51.610 --> 00:04:53.141
that's what we had called it,

00:04:53.141 --> 00:04:55.089
was elfin syndrome.

00:04:55.089 --> 00:04:57.845
The genetic cause of this
disorder was discovered

00:04:57.845 --> 00:05:02.011
in the 90s by my colleague Colleen Morris.

00:05:02.011 --> 00:05:04.741
So it's been a very interesting evolution.

00:05:04.741 --> 00:05:08.908
Since that time physicians'
sort of index of suspicion,

00:05:10.754 --> 00:05:14.992
their ability to pick up if
there was a failure to thrive

00:05:14.992 --> 00:05:18.558
or a particular facial
construct in babies,

00:05:18.558 --> 00:05:21.184
in small children, has increased.

00:05:21.184 --> 00:05:25.020
And there's a much greater recognition now

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:29.187
and of course a great interest
in neurobiology and behavior.

00:05:32.511 --> 00:05:34.178
