00:35:36.548 --> 00:35:39.776
So here's a question for Simon Fisher,

00:35:39.776 --> 00:35:42.668
are there people born
with speech disability

00:35:42.668 --> 00:35:45.778
but who have normal
other verbal abilities.

00:35:45.778 --> 00:35:49.945
I'm assuming reading comprehension
abilities, for example.

00:35:50.872 --> 00:35:51.705
- Yes.

00:35:53.529 --> 00:35:57.544
There's a lot of different types of speech

00:35:57.544 --> 00:35:59.961
and language disorders,

00:35:59.961 --> 00:36:01.294
many of them are

00:36:02.405 --> 00:36:04.747
have high heritability.

00:36:04.747 --> 00:36:07.733
There are some speech problems that are

00:36:07.733 --> 00:36:11.900
very predominantly just
about the kind of dysarthric,

00:36:12.996 --> 00:36:15.207
so you can have a developmental dysarthria

00:36:15.207 --> 00:36:16.779
that means you actually have problems

00:36:16.779 --> 00:36:19.320
physically making the
right kind of sounds.

00:36:19.320 --> 00:36:21.872
In some cases you can
have a combination of

00:36:21.872 --> 00:36:24.712
speech apraxia and dysarthria,

00:36:24.712 --> 00:36:27.346
although it's hard to pull those apart.

00:36:27.346 --> 00:36:29.929
You can have children who have,

00:36:32.144 --> 00:36:34.485
there are many kids that we study who have

00:36:34.485 --> 00:36:37.683
language impairments,
expressive receptive kind

00:36:37.683 --> 00:36:39.595
of language impairments but

00:36:39.595 --> 00:36:42.069
they actually, their speech,

00:36:42.069 --> 00:36:44.695
their sequencing abilities are normal.

00:36:44.695 --> 00:36:48.513
So there's a range of different
profiles of different kids,

00:36:48.513 --> 00:36:51.102
and often it's quite messy.

00:36:51.102 --> 00:36:54.195
In the early days of studying,

00:36:54.195 --> 00:36:58.355
of looking for genes for
involved in language disorders,

00:36:58.355 --> 00:37:00.711
there were some people
who were really focusing

00:37:00.711 --> 00:37:03.528
on trying to find a gene
for grammar, for example,

00:37:03.528 --> 00:37:07.694
or finding specific
lesions that might just

00:37:07.694 --> 00:37:11.111
take out one aspect of language function.

00:37:12.591 --> 00:37:15.669
And I think most of that
has proved not to be true.

00:37:15.669 --> 00:37:17.566
So it's a kind of gray area between

00:37:17.566 --> 00:37:19.649
some kids have relatively

00:37:22.023 --> 00:37:23.190
profiles where

00:37:24.479 --> 00:37:27.502
certain aspects are more
impaired than others.

00:37:27.502 --> 00:37:29.565
Many kids have these
kind of messy profiles

00:37:29.565 --> 00:37:32.178
but speech problems can
definitely be disassociated from

00:37:32.178 --> 00:37:34.394
linguistic problems as well.

00:37:34.394 --> 00:37:35.725
I don't know if that's fully answered the,

00:37:35.725 --> 00:37:38.599
I've gone in a few different directions.

00:37:38.599 --> 00:37:39.871
- Yeah, thanks.

